Brewster’s angle is the angle of incidence at which the reflection coefficient for the component whose electric-field vector lies in the plane of incidence (p-polarization) becomes zero.  “Vertical” polarization in the usual horizontal‐surface geometry is p-polarization, because the electric field points up–down inside the vertical plane that contains the incident and refracted rays.

If the incoming light is already 100 % vertically (p-) polarized, the component that could be reflected has an amplitude reflection coefficient of zero at θB. Consequently

• no light is reflected;  
• the entire beam is transmitted (aside from any absorption in the second medium);  
• the polarization of the transmitted beam is unchanged.

So at Brewster’s angle a 100 % vertically polarized incident beam simply enters the second medium with essentially no reflection.
